We “derive” the taxes payable amount by “summing‐up” the “tax_amount” on the Sale transactions (which are the only ones with any tax info) during the period. (There is no tax amount in the beginning “Initial” transactions so the initial taxes payable value is zero.) 

Using the provided records we “locate” every row where the type is “Sale” and then “add together” their tax_amount values. For example, one Sale has tax_amount = 5271.39, the next 3653.32, then 495.96, 1937.95, 1987.52, 1949.85, … and so on. (There are many such rows.) When all the tax_amount values from the Sale rows are summed the total comes to 252246.99. 

Thus the taxes payable in the opening balance (“Initial”) remain 0.00 while at “End–of–period” the cumulative sales–generated tax liability is 252246.99.

The answer is therefore:

{
  "solution": {
    "Taxes Payable Initial Value": "0.00",
    "Taxes Payable End Value": "252246.99"
  }
} 

Note: (The “step‐by–step” method was to identify sale rows, extract their tax_amount values and add them. Because the initial entries do not include any tax data the beginning balance for taxes payable starts at zero and grows solely as a result of sales tax accrued.)
